This research analysed a chain of relationships between employee skills, manufacturing flexibility and business performance in the automotive industry. As shown in figure, all the three dimensions of manufacturing flexibility were shown to be positively and significantly influenced by employees’ skills, corroborating that manufacturing flexibility is significantly improved by a commitment to continuous developments of multi-skilled workforces. The employees' skills have a positive influence on business performance. Results also show that n.p.flexibility, v.flexibility or mix flexibility, either do are significantly related to business performance. Our research suggests that manufacturing flexibility does have a positive significant direct effect on business performance.

All ten hypotheses achieved significant results statistically. The paths demonstrate positive relationships between the constructs, meaning that when a specified construct moves positively or negatively, another specified construct will move positively and negatively correspondingly. The standardised coefficients of the ten paths range from 0.17 to 0.65. The three most significant paths are international strat brand performance; control of marketing activities determining comm; and comm determining strat; with standardised coefficients of 0.65, 0.56 and 0.52, respectively. These results firstly indicate the importance of strat, which can enhance a firm’s brand performance by 0.65 standardised points for every standardised point increase in strat. Secondly, control of marketing activities is an important determinant of international commitment such that an increase of one standardised point of extent of control of marketing activities will lead to 0.56 standardised points of international commitment. Finally, international commitment is a critical input to international marketing strategy. Every single standardised point of increase in international commitment can lead to an increase of international marketing strategy by 0.52 standardised points.

This model confirmed that Processes has a significant direct relationship with Goals (with path coefficient =0.90), and it explains and influences 82 percent of the variance in Goals. As previously mentioned, the value of SEM lies in its ability to depict both the direct and indirect effects between the variables. In light of this, the best-fit model appears to indicate that People strongly influences Partnerships and resources, whereas Partnerships and resources moderately influences Policy and Strategy. Both People and Policy and strategy, were found to have significant direct relationships with Processes (with path coefficient =0.46 and 0.62, respectively). No statistically significant relationship, however, was found between Partnerships and resources, and Processes, indicating the absence of a direct effect. An indirect effect, though, exists through Policy and strategy. Partnerships and resources was found to have a positive impact on Policy and strategy (path coefficient =0.36) which, in turn, influences Processes. It is worth noting that R2 for Processes was 0.99, demonstrating that 99 per cent of the variance associated with Processes was accounted for by its two predictors, namely People and Policy and strategy. Leadership shows significant direct relationship with People (path coefficient =0.64) and Policy and strategy (path coefficient =0.59), but surprisingly bears no statistically significant relationship with Partnerships and resources. The relatively strong influence People had on Partnerships and resources (path coefficient =0.86) suggests that Leadership indirectly influences Partnerships and resources through People.

This measurement model includes five major scales: perception of test design (p-test design), perception of test uses (p-test uses), expectation, test value, and test preparation (Test prep). The p-test design scale has four subscales: perceived test demand for linguistic knowledge, perceived test demand for reading skills, perceived test demand for listening skills, and perceived test demand for writing skills. In this measurement model, the latent factor of p-test design represents the degree of test takers’ positive endorsement of test design. The higher the endorsement of liguistic knowledge as necessary for test taking, the more the test takers perceived test design as positive. Endorsement of test demand is also indicative of test takers’ knowledge of the test. The test preparation scale includes five sub-scales representing five types of test preparation practices: using socio-affective strategies to seek external help and to motivate oneself, conducting test analysis via assessing test requirements and evaluating oneself, memorizing vocabulary and model essays, drilling target language skills, and rehearsing test-taking skills. The latent factor of Test Prep represents the degree of engagement in preparation indicated by coherent uses of various strategies.

Figure shows the standardized path coefficients and the overall fit indexes. Since the goodness-of-fit measures are within the range of recommended levels, the model should be acceptable. While cost-saving, convenience, selection, and information availability has positive influence on utilitarian motivation, lack of sociality, and customized product and service has no causal relationships with utilitarian motivation. On the other hand, while adventure/explore, and authority and status have positive influence on hedonic motivation, social, idea, and value have no causal relationships with hedonic motivation. Utilitarian and hedonic motivations have significant impact on search intention. Utilitarian motivation and search intention have significant impact on purchase intention. The study shows that factors influencing utilitarian motivation are led by convenience, followed by cost saving, information availability and selection (judging by the level of standardized path coefficient). The factors influencing hedonic motivation are adventure/explore, authority and status accordingly. Both utilitarian motivation and hedonic motivation would influence search intention, of which utilitarian motivation was more influential. Utilitarian motivation would directly or indirectly influence purchase intention via search intention while hedonic motivation could only indirectly influence purchase intention via search intention. In summary, utilitarian motivation is more important than hedonic motivation in terms of influencing search or purchase intention. This study tries to determine whether a direct relationship exists between hedonic motivation and purchase intention. No significant relationship has been found. This study also tries to discover whether any hidden relationships exist between different kinds of values and shopping motivations. The result did not find any utilitarian values that would influence hedonic motivation and vice versa.

Figure reports all standardized path coefficients and presents the relationships among constructs in the model. Specifically, role stress has an indirect effect on turnover intention through burnout. Role stress was strongly associated with burnout (β = 0.70), but not directly with turnover intention. Burnout was significantly associated with turnover intention among social workers (β = 0.41). This suggests that burnout mediates the relationship between role stress and turnover intention. Regarding the effects of social support and job autonomy, the results only partially support that social support and job autonomy are negatively associated with burnout and turnover intention. Social support (β = −0.19) and job autonomy (β = − 0.19) were negatively associated with turnover intention, while job autonomy and social support were not associated with burnout. The interaction term between job autonomy and role stress was negatively significant in explaining burnout, which suggests that the relationship between role stress and burnout is stronger when job autonomy is lower. Furthermore, an interaction term between social support and role stress was negatively associated with turnover intention, which suggests that the relationship between role stress and turnover intention is stronger when social support is lower. Regarding demographic variables in the model, age was significantly associated with burnout (β = −0.11). In addition, organizational tenure (β = 0.20) and annual salary (β = −0.14) were associated with turnover intention, indicating that workers with longer organizational tenure and lower annual salary have greater intention to quit.

Whereas teacher support, task orientation and equity had significant direct effects on attitude to subject, four classroom scales (viz. teacher support, task orientation, computer usage, and young adult ethos) had significant direct effects on attitude to computer use. In general, the strength and direction of the statistically significant path coefficients are plausible. For example, teacher support was a moderate, positive predictor of attitude to subject (β = 0.33). Increased levels of involvement were positively related to academic efficacy (β = 0.29) which itself was related positively to attitude to subject (β = 0.21). That is, academic efficacy mediated the effect of involvement on attitude to subject. Task orientation was a significant, positive predictor of all three outcomes scales: academic efficacy (β = 0.23), attitude to subject (β = 0.16), and attitude to computer use (β = 0.12). The effects of most classroom environment scales on attitude to subject were mediated by academic efficacy. For example, the effect of differentiation on attitude to subject was mediated by academic efficacy (0.19 × 0.21 = 0.04). Task orientation’s direct effect on attitude to subject (β = 0.16) was complemented by a small indirect effect (0.23 × 0.21 = 0.04) due to the path via academic efficacy. The mediating effect of academic efficacy on attitude to subject is particularly noteworthy with four classroom environment scales in the model having only indirect effects on attitude to subject (involvement, investigation, differentiation and computer usage). The most striking aspect of the final model is that none of the three antecedent variables had a significant direct effect on the three outcome variables. In fact six of the eight classroom environment scales in the model mediated the effect of antecedents on outcomes. All antecedents had positive effects on classroom environment. First of all, the association of greening the supplier with environmental performance (H5) is significant (c = 0.39). Secondly, managerial innovation (H2b) and process innovation (H2a) are positively associated with environmental performance (b = 1.26 and 1.04, respectively). However, managerial innovation (H2c), surprisingly, did not show a significant relationship with environmental performance(b = -0.13). In other words, green product and process innovations may be more effective than green managerial innovations in improving a company’s environmental performance. This might be because managerial innovation has a more indirect effect on the measurement of environmental performance, compared to the other two types of inno vation. Managerial innovation relates to high level strategy and hence it is positively linked to competitive advantage. The results imply that managerial innovation may have a moderating effect on product and process innovation. Thirdly, the associations between greening the supplier and product innovation (H1a), process innovation (H1b), and managerial innovation (H1c) are also highly significant (c = 0.99, 0.93, and 0.95, respectively). In addition, product innovation (H3a), process innovation (H3b) and managerial innovation (H3c) all have positive path associations with competitive advantage (b = 0.59, 0.6, and 0.72, respectively). Finally, the associations between managerial innovation and product innovation (H7c) and process innovation (H7b) are significant (b = 1.04 and 0.94, respectively). Similarly, the path association between green product innovation and green process innovation (b = 0.92, p < 0.001) provides support for H7a. Green product innovation therefore contributes to green process innovation, and green managerial innovation contributes to both green product innovation and green process innovation, as shown in figure. More importantly, the intervening variable of innovation contributes to the relationship between greening the supplier and competitive advantage.

All coefficients and correlations were estimated using the full model. The latent variable, shadow economy, is constructed using its four indicators introduced above. The Corruption Perception Index (correlation 0.95), shadow economy survey (0.87) and cash quota (0.70) are the stronger indicators. The tax cheating survey (0.14) is the weakest indicator with nearly no influence, which confirms the previous assumptions. The latent variable, wealth a development level is constructed with two stronger indicators Human Development Index (0.97) and GDP per capita (0.93), and the weaker indicator Gini coefficient (−0.47) for inequality, which implies that more wealth reduces the shadow economy. The latent variable administrative system is constructed with 14 indicators,2 which are mainly based on surveys concerning the quality of institutions, regulations and bureaucratic procedures with the result, that a better administrative system sustainably reduces the shadow economy. The latent variable, constitutional trust and values is based on 11 indicators,3 with surveys and indices concerning the trust in constitutional functions such as the rule of law (0.96), democratic accountability (0.85) or regime durability (0.71). This latent variable has a high negative correlation (−0.89) but only a minor coefficient (−0.07) with shadow economy. Countries with higher constitutional trust and values have less shadow economy, but this influence disappears in the mul tivariate model, because the remaining latent variables already include all useful information. The three independent latent variables have a high multicollinearity between 0.81 and 0.90, meaning it is not exactly possible to distinguish their influence on the shadow economy. All of the three independent latent variables could be combined into a single variable, Overall state. The partialR2 = 0.90 was calculated using the reduced model and it shows that the Overall State explains major parts of the variations of the shadow economy.

Information, convenience, and social interaction showed significant direct effects on the duration of time on a Web site. On the other hand, the model revealed that duration of time had nonsignificant direct effects on the human–message interaction, the human–human interaction, and attitude toward the site. The information motivation had a positive effect on human–message interaction, which suggests that those who have high information motivation tend to click a series of hyperlinks as a voluntary exposure to further information provided on advertiser Web sites. The social interaction motivations had a positive effect on human–human interaction . It is interesting to note that the social-interaction motivation had a negative effect on human–message interaction . Convenience motivation had a positive effect on human–human interaction, but little effect on human–message interaction. The results imply that those who have high convenience motivation are more likely to use interactive features promoting interactions among people rather than human–message interactive features.Attitude toward the site was more strongly affected by the human–human interaction than the human–message interaction, while the human–message interaction also had a significant direct effect on the variable. This result indicates that if a Web site gets visitors interacting with other people, it is expected that this site can achieve more positive outcomes from the visitors. The causal relations between interactivity and attitude toward the site were significantly positive. Attitude toward the brand was strongly affected by attitude toward the site. In addition, the indirect effect of attitude toward the site on purchase intention via attitude toward the brand was also significantly positive. On the other hand, attitude toward the brand had a strong effect on purchase in tention.

The results of the structural model are presented in figure. Accountants’ participation in strategic decision making processes is positively associated with strategy type prospector/defender and deliberate strategy formulation. SMA usage is positively associated with three of the four contingent factors (strategy type prospector/defender, deliberate strategy formulation, and company size), and also accountants’ participation in strategic decision making processes (explaining 62% of the variation in SMA usage). The structural model indicates that SMA usage is not associated with market orientation, although in the measurement model there is a relatively strong correlation between the two constructs. It is also interesting that accountants' participation in strategic decision making processes does not directly influence performance, however an indirect effect exists between ccountants' participation in strategic decision making processes and performance via SMA usage. From a holistic perspective, the model is dominated by a very strong direct effect of market orientation on performance. SMA usage is positively affected by the adoption of a strategy type prospector/defender and a deliberate strategy formulation (both directly and indirectly via participation), and company size, while SMA usage, in turn, positively affects performance.

In this sample, siblings and media did not retain their relations to greater identification as a smoker, suggesting that this pathway may be more important after an adolescent has first tried smoking. Having peers and siblings who smoke was related to higher normative beliefs about smoking, but again norms were not associated with smoking intentions. Exposure to peer, parent, and media smoking were associated with endorsement of positive expectancies about smoking, which was in turn related to smoking intentions. In this initiation model, the role of media exposure to smoking seemed to have the strongest association with intentions to smoke through the expectancies variable. This model confirmed the negative relationship between parental media restriction and exposure to smoking in media, in that children whose parents restricted media were less likely to begin smoking. In addition, the model retained the added pathway between peer smoking and intentions to smoke, highlighting the importance of peers in the initiation of adolescent smoking.

Cancer-related distress and intrusive rumination were related to social constraints; however, contrary to predictions, social constraints within close relationships did not play a significant direct role in perceived PTG. Small indirect relationships were also evident between challenge appraisal and examining core beliefs with PTG. As seen in figure, multiple potential pathways were evident between these variables and growth. The main hypotheses of the research have been accepted. The potential flexibility has a powerful impact on actual flexibility. The potential flexibility also had a direct impact on static complexity. The acceptance of all three main hypotheses of the research yields to the following practical implications. First of all, it was recognized that there is cause and effect relations among flexibility dimensions. This means that if we would like to improve the actual flexibility as emergent flexibility of a manufacturing system, we may invest on potential flexibility dimensions. Moreover, potential flexibility has a strong root in basic flexibility. These interactions help the managers to plan the improvement projects of manufacturing systems effectively. These interactions can be followed in the lowest level of indicators of the flexibility dimensions for more practical suggestions through path analysis as accomplished in this research. We also find that static complexity receives a direct impact from potential flexibility. This chain, i.e. the serial impacts of flexibility dimensions and the static complexity help managers to tune the manufacturing systems on the basis of these perspectives.

The first notable and unexpected result was the very strong effect from POLICY to STREET (b = .446). This strong positive relationship indicates that – contrary to our expectations – those who did policy work were also likely to do street level activities, meaning that these positions and tasks were far from mutually exclusive. However, greater engagement in policy activities did imply a greater involvement in provincial (b = .313), national (b = .376) as well as long (b = .191), and FIRE (b = .151) issues. Also contrary to what we expected, the SEM analysis revealed that many analysts who were more involved in PROVINCIAL were also engaged in LONG (g = .112). National issue work also was accompanied with FIRE (g = .132) and LONG (g = .119), again suggesting that these forms of activities are also not oppositional: those who do more of one tend to do more of the other.
